{"id":"astro-ph/0210543","submitter":"Bryan Gaensler","authors":"Bryan Gaensler (1), Heath Jones (2, 3), Ben Stappers (4, 5) ((1)\n  Harvard-Smithsonian CfA, (2) ESO, (3) U Chile, (4) ASTRON, (5) U Amsterdam)","title":"An optical bow shock around the nearby millisecond pulsar J2124-3358","comments":"6 pages, uses emulateapj, ApJ Letters, in press","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1086/345750","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We report the discovery of an H-alpha-emitting bow-shock nebula powered by\nthe nearby millisecond pulsar J2124-3358. The bow shock is very broad, and is\nhighly asymmetric about the pulsar's velocity vector. This shape is not\nconsistent with that expected for the case of an isotropic wind interacting\nwith a homogeneous ambient medium. Models which invoke an anisotropy in the\npulsar wind, a bulk flow of the surrounding gas, or a density gradient in the\nambient medium either perpendicular or parallel to the pulsar's direction of\nmotion also fail to reproduce the observed morphology. However, we find an\nensemble of good fits to the nebular morphology when we consider a combination\nof these effects. In all such cases, we find that the pulsar is propagating\nthrough an ambient medium of mean density 0.8-1.3 cm^(-3) and bulk flow\nvelocity ~15-25 km/s and that the star has recently encountered an increase in\ndensity by 1-10 cm^(-3) over a scale ~<0.02 pc. The wide variety of models\nwhich fit the data demonstrate that in general there is no unique set of\nparameters which can be inferred from the morphology of a bow-shock nebula.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 24 Oct 2002 14:57:49 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-07"}
